I don't expect you to understand how hard it was dealing with something like this. It's a condition that doesn't have a lot of light shed on it and for you maybe cats and ameristralia are front page worthy but I believe if I can inspire others who are experiencing the same thing. Yes, there are those who pull out their entire head of hair, sorry it my life's life changing event pissed you off.

The way you describe the feeling sounds similar to the way it makes me feel. Might be trich. Catch yourself doing it so you try to become more aware and it becomes less of a compulsive behavior. You can do it!
Hence my comment with pictures of myself throughout the years.

It's never too late, there's always time to beat it no matter what kind of damage has been done. I still have some skin picking issues with acne on my back but ultimately I know if I continue to do it, it will never even begin to heal. Positivity, again anyone who would want someone to talk to I can be there even if it's just to talk.
I was nervous at first, but I honestly believe by showing what I could accomplished through determination and perseverance, others can achieve as well using it as a means of inspiration.

Your daughter is very fortunate to have such understanding and helpful friends, along with loving and supportive parents. It's people like you that remind me to remain optimistic. I'm glad she has overcome the hardest part, once they are back she will no doubt feel powerful, strong, and confident. Thank you for your kind words, Reddit blows me away sometimes.

A dermatologist told me when I was round about 14 that if I continued to pull them out they would eventually never grow back due to the amount of scar tissue I was building up. I consider myself very lucky.
